{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}} {{about||the United States Navy aviator|Beverley Randolph (aviator)|the educator|Beverley Randolph Mason}} {{Infobox Governor |name = Beverley Randolph |image = |order = 8th |office = Governor of Virginia |term_start = December 1, 1788 |term_end = December 1, 1791 |predecessor = [[Edmund Randolph]] |successor = [[Henry Lee III]] |birth_date = {{birth year|1754}} |birth_place = [[Henrico County, Virginia|Henrico County]], [[Colony of Virginia]], [[British America]] |death_date = {{death date and given age|1797|2|7|42–43}} |death_place = [[Cumberland County, Virginia|Cumberland County]], [[Virginia]], [[United States|U.S.]] |resting_place = Westview Cemetery, [[Farmville, Virginia]] |party = |spouse = Martha Cocke |alma_mater = [[The College of William and Mary]] }} '''Beverley Randolph''' (1754{{spaced ndash}}February 7, 1797) was an [[American politician]] from [[Virginia]]. From 1788 to 1791, he served as the [[List of Governors of Virginia|eighth]] [[Governor of Virginia]].
==Biography== Randolph was one of four children born to Peter Randolph, son of [[William Randolph II]], and Lucille (Bolling) Randolph, at [[Turkey Island (James River)|Turkey Island]], a plantation in [[Henrico County, Virginia|Henrico County]] in the [[Colony of Virginia]].<ref name="Page">{{cite book |last1=Page |first1=Richard Channing Moore |title=Genealogy of the Page Family in Virginia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cOBBAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate= |edition=2 |year=1893 |month= |publisher=Press of the Publishers Printing Co. |location=New York |isbn= |pages=249–272 |chapter=Randolph Family |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=cOBBAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA247#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref><ref name="Robert Isham Randolph">{{cite book |last1=Randolph |first1=Robert Isham |title=The Randolphs of Virginia: A Compilation of the Descendants of William Randolph of Turkey Island and His Wife Mary Isham Of Bermuda Hundred |url=http://randolpharchives.org/books/Randolphs_of_Virginia_001-052.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate= |year=1936 |month= |publisher= |isbn= }}</ref> One of Randolph's siblings was Ann Bolling Randolph Fitzhugh, wife of [[William Fitzhugh]].<ref name="Robert Isham Randolph"/>
Randolph was educated at [[The College of William and Mary]] and married Martha Cocke in 1775. He served in the militia during the [[American Revolutionary War]], was a member of the [[Virginia Assembly]] and was a member of the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] from 1777 to 1780. When [[George Wythe]] withdrew from the [[Philadelphia Convention of 1787]], [[George Mason]] suggested that Randolph (who happened to be in [[Philadelphia]] at the time) be appointed in his place. The Council and governor decided that in light of the abilities of Virginia's remaining delegates, Wythe did not need to be replaced. Randolph was elected [[Governor of Virginia]] in 1788, the first to be elected after Virginia ratified the [[United States Constitution]]. He died on his farm near Green Creek in [[Cumberland County, Virginia]].
