'''Bleached Chemi-ThermoMechanical Pulp''' (BCTMP) is a pulp product used by the [[paper industry]] as a less expensive alternative for Northern Bleached Softwood Kraft (NBSK).

BCTMP was first produced by Millar Western in 1988 in its Whitecourt Mill, and was initially used in lower grade paper applications.<ref name="Pulp & Paper CA article - BCTMP">{{cite journal|last1=Rodden|first1=Graeme|title=BCTMP: A PULP FOR ALL REASONS?|journal=Pulp & Paper Canada|date=2000-09-01|issue=September 2000|url=http://www.pulpandpapercanada.com/news/bctmp-a-pulp-for-all-reasons/1000106738/?&er=NA|accessdate=2015-02-16}}</ref>  The product is attractive to producers because it needed less capital to construct the production facilities and provides higher yields than other processes which lowers the total cost of production.  In addition, BCTMP provides higher bulk, opacity and stiffness in the final product and the process is more environmentally friendly.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cannell|first1=Eric|title=The Future of BCTMP|url=http://www.risiinfo.com/db_area/archive/p_p_mag/2000/0005/feat2.htm|website=www.risiinfo.com/|publisher=Pulp & Paper|accessdate=2015-02-16}}</ref>

