[[File:125 Worth Street health jeh.JPG|thumb|125 Worth Street]] '''Worth Street''' is a two-way street running roughly northwest-southeast in [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]. It runs from [[Hudson Street (Manhattan)|Hudson Street]], [[TriBeCa]], in the west to [[Chatham Square, Manhattan|Chatham Square]] in [[Chinatown, Manhattan|Chinatown]] in the east. Past Chatham Square, the roadway continues as Oliver Street, a north-south street running [[one-way traffic|one-way]] northbound. Between [[West Broadway]] and [[Church Street (Manhattan)|Church Street]], Worth Street is also known as [[John Marshall Harlan II|Justice John M. Harlan Way]] in honor of the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] justice and alumnus of the nearby [[New York Law School]]. Between [[Centre Street (Manhattan)|Centre]] and [[Baxter Street]]s, Worth Street is also known as the "Avenue of the Strongest", "New York's Strongest" being a nickname for the city's [[New York City Department of Sanitation|Department of Sanitation]].<ref>{{cite web | title="Avenue Of The Strongest" To Honor New York City Sanitation Workers | website=Waste360 | date=1996-08-01 | url=http://waste360.com/mag/waste_avenue_strongest_honor | accessdate=2016-02-06}}</ref>
Worth Street passes through the cluster of government offices and courthouses centered on [[Foley Square]]. 125 Worth Street (at [[Centre Street (Manhattan)|Centre Street]]) houses the headquarters of the [[New York City Health and Hospitals Corporation]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Contact | website=NYC Health and Hospitals | date=2015-10-19 | url=http://www.nychealthandhospitals.org/hhc/html/contact/Contact.shtml | accessdate=2016-02-06}}</ref> the Department of Health and Mental Hygiene,<ref>{{cite web | title=Ordering In Person or By Mail | website=Welcome to NYC.gov | date=2015-08-07 | url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/doh/html/services/vr-order-other.shtml | accessdate=2016-02-06 | quote = NYC Department of Health and Mental Hygiene, Office of Vital Records, 125 Worth St.}}</ref> and the Department of Sanitation.<ref>{{cite web | title=Business - Nonputrescible, | website=City of New York, Solid Waste Transfer Station | url=https://www1.nyc.gov/nycbusiness/description/solid-waste-transfer-station-nonputrescible | accessdate=2016-02-06}}</ref> Additionally, the [[New York Supreme Court]] courthouses at [[60 Centre Street]] and 80 Centre Street (the [[Louis Lefkowitz|Louis J. Lefkowitz]] Building) and the [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] Federal Courthouse ([[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York|Southern District of New York]]) at 500 [[Pearl Street (Manhattan)|Pearl Street]] all have entrances facing Worth Street.
== History == What is now Worth Street originally started at the [[Five Points (Manhattan)|Five Points]] intersection and headed west; it was known as Anthony Street. In 1797, it was named Catherine Street (separately from the other Catherine Street to the southeast, which remains today, as well as another one to the north). Starting at [[Hudson Street (Manhattan)|Hudson Street]], it ended at the western bank of the [[Collect Pond]]. Catherine Lane, which ran parallel and to the north,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/iconographyofman01stok#page/n661/mode/2up|title=A New and Accurate Plan of the City of New York in the State of New York in North America.|last=|first=|date=1797|website=Internet Archive|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=Jun 29, 2018}}</ref> still exists as an alleyway between Broadway and Lafayette Street. An 1807 map shows that the pond was filled in, and that Anthony Street ran to an unlabeled short street where Centre Street is now.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geographicus.com/P/AntiqueMap/NewYork-bridges-1871|title=Plan of the City of New York, with the recent and intended Improvements|last=Bridges|first=William|date=1807|website=Geographicus|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=Jun 29, 2018}}</ref> After 1811, Anthony Street was extended to Orange Street (later renamed Baxter Street), completing the "fifth point" of the intersection by bisecting its northeast corner. In 1854, it was renamed Worth Street in honor of Major-general [[William J. Worth]], hero of the 1848 [[Mexican–American War|Mexican War]]. Worth is buried two miles north in [[Worth Square]], which is at the north end of [[Madison Square]] near 26th Street.<ref>{{cite web | title=New York City Chinatown > Historical Photos > Canal Street and the Five Points | website=New York City Chinatown | date=2008-09-13 | url=http://www.nychinatown.org/history/1800s.html | accessdate=2016-02-06}}</ref> In 1868, the city opened the section from Five Points east to [[Chatham Square]].
A [[Worth Street (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)|station]] on the [[New York City Subway]]'s [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]] at Worth Street was open between 1904 and 1962.<ref>{{cite web | title=Abandoned Stations : Worth St | website=Columbia University in the City of New York | url=http://www.columbia.edu/~brennan/abandoned/worth.html | accessdate=2016-02-06}}</ref>
On February 5, 2016, a crane collapsed on Worth Street at [[60 Hudson Street]], killing one person and injuring two others.<ref>{{cite web | last=Brown | first=Nicole | last2=Reysen | first2=Jamie | title=Cops ID man, 38, killed in crane collapse | website=am New York | date=2016-02-05 | url=http://www.amny.com/news/nyc-crane-collapse-on-worth-street-in-tribeca-kills-1-injures-3-fdny-says-1.11432547 | accessdate=2016-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Tracy | first=Thomas | last2=Schapiro | first2=Rich | last3=Place | first3=Nathan | last4=Otis | first4=Ginger Adams | title=Construction crane collapse in Manhattan kills David Wichs | website=NY Daily News | date=2016-02-05 | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/construction-crane-collapses-manhattan-injures-2-article-1.2521130 | accessdate=2016-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=King | first=Kate | last2=Shallwani | first2=Pervaiz | title=Crane Collapses in Lower Manhattan, Killing One | website=WSJ | date=2016-02-05 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/crane-collapses-in-lower-manhattan-1454680767 | accessdate=2016-02-06}}</ref><ref name="BBC">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-35505329 |title=New York crane collapse kills at least one person |accessdate=February 6, 2016 |work=BBC News}}</ref>
